node.text:
Bowmar Archery Grip Tape! 
I dive deep in this video going into everything that Levi and I have put into this grip tape for over a year. Our goal was to help create the most constant grip possible, and I truly believe we’ve done it. Our weather resistant tacky polymer grip CANT BE BEAT in wet or sweaty conditions. On top of that, our heavily researched, developed, and tested grip pattern is specifically designed for archers keeping your hand from sliding left or right and up and down. I’m beyond excited to bring this product to all us archers. We truly believe it’ll make a huge difference for all levels, both PRO and beginner on keeping a constant grip.
We have 11 different colors to choose from, if you’d like to order please click the link in our profile, we appreciate your support more than you know!

node.text: This buck we knew well and I even hunted him back in 2019. He was ancient and by far the largest body deer I ever got on camera. With an estimated weight of over 300lbs! node.text:
WE DID IT!! I SHOT A NEW WORLD RECORD!! (Read last post for more of the story) I’m beyond myself and grateful to take such an unbelievable animal with a bow. The shot ended up being 118 yards not 120 like I thought, so I hit him a tick high, but I still smoked him and he ran 60 yards and piled up stone dead. This grant’s gazelle shatters the current world record  w/ a bow, measuring over 27 1/2 inches in length. He is the largest one shot in the past 4 years with any weapon. This ram is an absolute monster to say the least! I knew we were hunting something special when my PH that’s been hunting this ground for 10 years never seen a grants that big. To get him with any weapon would have been special, but to do it with a bow 100% wild and free ranging makes this achievement so much more rewarding. All the trackers and game scout (game warden) were so excited for this to come together for me, despite all the odds stacked against me using a bow. He’s truly a trophy for all of us. Everyone worked so hard to make this all come together, honestly, we all had our doubts at moments, but we pushed through and all the hard work and relentless effort payed off big! We captured it all on video, another hunt of a lifetime for me that I’ll talk about for the rest of my life. There’s no doubt, i’m the happiest bow hunter on the planet! @bowmar_archery 
#worldrecord #freeranging #100%wild
PS: in Tanzania, at all times, there has to be a game scout (game warden) with you. Pretty weird, but also really cool! They’ve been incredibly kind and helpful the whole trip. It’s truly amazing how much Tanzania protects their wildlife.

node.text: We made our move! With us having no time left, we had to get aggressive . We decided to bump the big herd in hopes he would split off. As luck would have it, our plan worked! He split with another ram from the group and took off. Little did we know how much work was ahead of us once we spooked him. He went far REALLY REALLY FAR,  We tracked this beast on foot for over 10 MILES before we caught up to him. We picked up our pace and got within 200 yards and just kept following waiting for him to bed down, or stop in the shade to close the final distance, but he never stopped for more than 3 secs before moving again. But finally we caught a break! He started moving up this steep small rocky ridge, that at the top was a flat bushy desert. I knew this was my chance to close the distance to bow range. Once he cleared the top, I could sprint up the small mountain without him seeing us, come over the top of the ridge and he should be within bow range. So that’s exactly what I did. The moment he cleared the top, I took off sprinting up the rocky face and right before the top, I slowed down and peaked over the ridge and there he was. He made it further than I thought, he was standing there broadside at 107 yards. I drew my bow, but he already started walking again. He was walking straight away from me on this angled rock that exposed everything from the base of his head all the way to his tail. I knew I wasn’t getting another opportunity, this was my chance and I was going to take it. Still full draw I knew he went about 13 yards, putting him at 120. At this distance the arrow would be coming in from a very steep downward angle that would drive straight through his cavity as if he was directly under me. I calmed my breath, relaxed my hands, my arms, my whole body, everything had to be perfect. There was zero room for error at this distance, despite running up the mountain, I felt really steady so I held for 120 and ran my shot. Everything was in slow motion as I watched my arrow fly through the air. All the miles on our boots, all the hard work was riding on this shot. As my arrow got closer and closer, we all stood and watched for what felt like an eternity.

node.text: What a great day! We got back on that freak giant grants, but Still can’t get into bow range. Their eye sight is incredible and there’s 30 of them. The more we look at this guy, the more and more special he gets. He’s tall, long, and heavy. Our PH “Lorn” has been hunting the Maasai land for over 10 years and never seen anything like him. We need him to break off from the herd for us to have a chance. To get this caliber of a grant gazelle with any weapon would be an incredible feat, let alone a bow. Tomorrow’s a new day, and we still have time.

node.text: Hard to close the distance with this many eye balls. We have spotted one of the biggest grant’s our PH has ever seen 😳 this monster has become top priority now. We’re going all in every day for him. This could be the largest ram ever killed with a bow and one of the largest ever killed period if we can pull it off. Problem is, these gazelles move constantly and cover miles and miles and miles everyday. With bow hunting, here’s a time to be aggressive and a time to be patient. With us having a few days left, we’re going with the patient move. If we push him to hard he could be gone forever. With this many eye balls we have no chance, we need him to break off from the main herd. Today wasn’t the day, maybe tomorrow will be different.

node.text: I shot a freaking beast of a Thompson’s gazelle! These little antelope have the best buttery flavored meat you could ever imagine 😳. Unfortunately for them, cheetahs have figured this out too. So over time the “Tommies”  evolved to be extremely fast and they never stop moving, In fact, they’re one of the fastest antelope in all of Africa, which creates a extreme challenge for any bow hunter to get close and get a shot. All week we’ve been looking for an old monster and finally at last light we spotted this monster “Tommy” with some females. But like always he never stopped moving. We tried to get close to the herd, but they just kept moving further away and this old beast was at the back. We were following behind about 115  yards and our luck changed! He stopped to pee, I knew this was my chance, I took off running and got to 86 yards, cranked my sight and drew my bow before he stopped doing his business. He was steeping quartering away with a slight cross wind. On such a small target I knew I needed to be perfect. My pin settled in the middle and I cut it loose! My arrow flew true and smoked him, but just a tick low. He took off running and stopped at 96 yards. I already had another arrow knocked, drew my bow and put another one in him and smoked him again. He took off sprinting full speed and didn’t make far before he piled up. These african animals are honestly the toughest animals on the planet. I didn’t realize just how big he was until I got up to him and put my hands on him. After measuring him, turns out he’s the 4th largest Thompson’s gazelle ever killed with a bow! I couldn’t be more proud of such a cool animal. The fact he makes the record books is a pretty incredible bonus. @bowmar_archery #100%wild #bowhunting

node.text: The amount of respect I have for this animal cant be quantified. For a bull this mature to stay alive and live amongst lions, leopards, hyenas, disease, and other bulls  just shows you how tough and resilient they really are.  But at the end of the day, nothing dies of old age in the wild. At some point, the harsh reality sets in and Mother Nature turns into a brutal serial killer on the old, weak, and unable. As a hunter, it’s always my goal to go after the old and mature animals regardless the weapon I choose to use. What separates a mature Cape buffalo bull and a young bull  is the bosses. When they are young and immature the bosses will be soft, but once they fully mature the bosses turn solid. As you can see from the photos, he has fully hard bosses. I couldn’t be happier and more proud of this african beast. I can’t wait to share all these amazing experiences with you. We’ve captured every moment on camera and truly some of the most incredibly encounters after captured on video.

node.text: I did it! 100% wild free ranging Cape buffalo  with my homemade longbow! This is one of the proudest moments of my life and one of my greatest accomplishments as a bow hunter. I couldn’t be more proud of this shot! Under 20 yards face to face with a Cape buffalo and not folding under pressure, but instead, making the best shot of my life. Releasing that arrow and watching it hit that Cape buffalo perfectly right behind the shoulder, double lunging him was the most surreal moment I’ve ever had in the bush. I can’t begin to put into words how much this buffalo means to me. All I can say is, a 100% wild, 100% free ranging Tanzania Cape buffalo with hard bosses with a homemade bow is my Everest in hunting. Truly an achievement of a lifetime. The best part is, I got the whole hunt  on film! I can’t wait to share it with you.
